05009nam a22005295i 9780822397465DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223974657 a10.1515/97808223974652doi  a(DE-B1597)553765  a(OCoLC)1229161197  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS518 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a303.48/273052211 aCumings, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParallax Visions :bMaking Sense of American-East Asian Relations at the End of the Century /cBruce Cumings. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (288 p.) :bDavid Whitehouse, International Socialist Review  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Archaeology, Descent, Emergence: American Mythology and East Asian Reality -- t2 East Wind, Rain Red Wind Black Rain: The United States-Japan War, Beginning and End -- t3 Colonial Formations and Deformations: Korea, Taiwan, and Vietnam -- t4 Civil Society and Democracy in the United States and East Asia -- t5 Nuclear Imbalance of Terror: The American Surveillance Regime and North Korea's Nuclear Program -- t6 The World Shakes China -- t7 Boundary Displacement: The State, the Foundations, and International and Area Studies during and after the Cold War -- t8 East Asia and the United States: Double Vision and Hegemonic Emergence -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a work that synthesizes crucial developments in international relations at the close of the twentieth century, Bruce Cumings-a leading historian of contemporary East Asia-provides a nuanced understanding of how the United States has loomed over the modern history and culture of East Asia. By offering correctives to widely held yet largely inaccurate assessments of the affairs of this region, Parallax Visions shows how relations between the United States, Japan, Vietnam, North and South Korea, China, and Taiwan have been structured by their perceptions and misperceptions of each other.Using information based on thirty years of research, Cumings offers a new perspective on a wide range of issues that originated with the cold war-with particular focus on the possibly inappropriate collaboration between universities, foundations, and intelligence agencies. Seeking to explode the presuppositions that Americans usually bring to the understanding of our relations with East Asia, the study ranges over much of the history of the twentieth century in East Asian-American relations-Pearl Harbor, Hiroshima and Nagasaki, the Korean War, and more recent difficulties in U.S. relations with China and Japan. Cumings also rebuts U.S. media coverage of North Korea's nuclear diplomacy in the 1990s and examines how experiences of colonialism and postcolonialism have had varying effects on economic development in each of these countries. Positing that the central defining experience of twentieth-century East Asia has been its entanglement first with British and Japanese imperialism, and then with the United States, Cumings ends with a discussion of how the situation could change over the next century as the economic and political global clout of the United States declines.Illuminating the sometimes self-deluded ideology of cold war America, Parallax Visions will engage historians, political scientists, and students and scholars of comparative politics and social theory, as well as readers interested in questions of modernity and the role of the United States in shaping the destinies of modernizing societies in Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397465zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397465.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles